\layout Subsection

Distribution of Rationals in the Farey Tree
\layout Standard

One way to enumerate all of the rationals is by placing them on the Farey
 Tree (or the Stern-Brocot Tree).
 One can prove that the Farey Tree enumerates all of the rationals in the
 unit interval exactly once (Proof at 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \htmlurl[Cut-the-Knot]{http://www.cut-the-knot.org/blue/Stern.shtml}

\end_inset 

).
 However, the distribution of the rationals on the Farey Tree is highly
 non-uniform, if we walk that tree breadth-first.
 The figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Distribution-of-Farey}

\end_inset 

 shows that distribution.
 This distribution is highly non-uniform, and by fooling with the number
 of bins in the histogram, it becomes clear that the figure is highly discontinu
ous.
 Remarkably, though, in a certain sense, the figure also stays uniform in
 a certain sense as the number of bins is increased: it always has this
 humped form, even though the individual spikes vary strongly according
 to the number of bins.
 
