This is really a very curious circumstance.
 The above graphs show only the distribution of a finite number of points
 (they were, after all, computer generated).
 A finite set of points on the real number line is zero; yet we are using
 it to induce a measure that can be used for integration.
 How is this? The statistical properties of a finite sampling provide us
 with information about the limit.
 Its as if we were working with an anti-Cantor-set construction: we start
 with a dust, and average over intervals to discover analytic properties.
\layout Subsection

Formal Treatment
\layout Standard

The previous section provided only a hand-waving intro.
 We need a formal treatment.
 To prove that the measure vanishes on rationals, we need to show two things:
 first, that the measure vanishes near 0 (or 1), in that the the bin count
 for bin 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset 

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and a few neighbors) is always bounded above by 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{-\alpha}$
\end_inset 

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>1$
\end_inset 

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 is probably quite large, and the bound can be made very strong.
 Next, one needs to show a modular group symmetry for the histogram: thus
 for example, that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{pN/q}$
\end_inset 

 obeys a similar bound, but derated by a factor given by the modular group
 element that carries 
\begin_inset Formula $0/1$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Subsection

Modular Forms
\layout Standard

A meromorphic function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\tau)$
\end_inset 

 is said to be a modular form of weight 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 if it has the moduar group symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f\left(\frac{a\tau+b}{c\tau+d}\right)=\left(c\tau+d\right)^{k}f\left(\tau\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 for integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ad-bc=1$
\end_inset 

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 is a complex number, restricted to the upper-half plane: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Im\tau>0$
\end_inset 

.
 Modular forms can also be expressed as a function of the nome 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\exp i\pi\tau$
\end_inset 

.
 In this form, many have the interesting property of having poles and zeros
 closely interspersed at the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $|q|\rightarrow1$
\end_inset 

, with poles (or zeros) occuring at rational angles, and the other at irrational
 angles.
 A particular example of this is the twenty-fourth root of the modular discrimin
ant, known as the Dedekind eta.
 
