This figure shows a particular slice through the Dedekind eta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=q^{1/24}\Pi_{n=1}^{\infty}(1-q^{2n})$
\end_inset 

.
 This figure graphs 
\begin_inset Formula $|\eta|$
\end_inset 

 along a particular curve: we take 
\begin_inset Formula $q=|q|e^{i\theta}$
\end_inset 

 and hold 
\begin_inset Formula $|q|=0.96$
\end_inset 

 fixed, while sweeping through values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset 

 from 0 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset 

.
 Several features of this figure should be noted.
 First, this function is continuous and infinitely differentiable for any
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $|q|<1$
\end_inset 

.
 Next, the Dedekind eta has a kind of modular group symmetry: if we write
 the nome 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\exp(i\pi\tau)$
\end_inset 

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $|\eta((a\tau+b)/(c\tau+d))|=|\sqrt{c\tau+d}\;\eta(\tau)|$
\end_inset 

 for integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ad-bc=1$
\end_inset 

.
 Finally, in the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $|q|\rightarrow1$
\end_inset 

, this function has a zero for all rational angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi m/n$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 are integers, but otherwise this function diverges for all non-rational
 angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset 

.
 As such, it has a superficial resemblance to 
\begin_inset Formula $d?(x)/dx$
\end_inset 

.
 
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Dedekind-Eta}

\end_inset 

 shows a particular cross-section through the Dedekind eta.
 Note the suggestive shape of this curve, and how it crudely resembles the
 distribution of the Farey fractions.
 Although it is clear that this curve will not converge to the derivative
 of the question mark in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $|q|\rightarrow1$
\end_inset 

, it none-the-less is suggestive.
 Notably, modular forms already have the modular group symmetry, and so
 already have the symmetry properties of the final curve that we are searching
 for.
 This is unlike the histograming approach, where the symmetry is obtained
 only in the limit.
 The other remarkable property is that modular forms are infinitely differentiab
le, and thus posees well-behaved analytic properties, again allowing a kind
 of studdy that is ill-afforded by the histograms.
\layout Standard

The presumption that we are making here is that the derivative of the Minkowski
 question mark function will be found to be the limit of some modular form,
 although which modular form that might be is not clear at this time.
 The theory of modular forms is deep andbroad, and will not be reviewed
 here; the following assumes a basic understanding.
 A very synoptic overview can be found in the article on elliptic functions
 in Wikipedia.
 An in-depth exposition can be found in the book by Apostol.
